CLASSICAL SWINE FEVER IN GERMANY
-------------------
(Date of last previously reported outbreak: July 2001).
Information received on 5 Oct 001 from:
Prof. Dr Werner Zwingmann
Chief Veterinary Officer
Ministry of Food, Agriculture and Forestry
Bonn:
Report date: 5 Oct 2001.
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 5 Oct 2001.
Location and No. of outbreaks: 1 in Spree-Neisse, Brandenburg Land.
Description of affected population: pigs for breeding.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
Number of susceptible: 2
Number of cases: 1
Number of deaths: 0
Number of destroyed: 2
Number of slaughtered: 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: European Union Reference Laboratory
for classical swine fever, Hannover.
B. Diagnostic tests used: direct immunofluorescence.
Source of agent / origin of infection: not yet known.
Control measures:
- The remaining animals were slaughtered and will be destroyed in
rendering plants.
- Prohibition on movements of animals of susceptible species in an
area around the infected holding.
- Tracing of animal movements into and out of the infected holding.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This site is far west of Hannover where the previous 2 reported cases of
Classical Swine Fever occurred last summer. - Mod.PC
